# Data Access Layer & API-Readiness Contract

## The Core Rule

**Components and features NEVER import directly from `src/lib/data/`.**

All data access — static or live — must go through `src/lib/api/`.
This is a hard contract that makes the backend migration zero-touch on components.

```
                        TODAY                          FUTURE
                        -----                          ------

  Page / Feature
  Component
       │
       │ imports                                          │ imports
       ▼                                                  ▼
  src/lib/api/          ◄──── only this layer       src/lib/api/
  products.js                 changes when           products.js
       │                      backend is ready            │
       │ reads from                                        │ fetches from
       ▼                                                  ▼
  src/lib/data/          ◄── currently               Real Backend API
  products.js                static arrays           (REST / GraphQL / DB)
```

---

## What This Means in Practice

### ✅ CORRECT — Component imports from `lib/api/`

```jsx
// app/(marketing)/products/page.jsx
import { getProducts } from '@/lib/api/products'   // ✅ through the API layer

export default async function ProductsPage() {
  const products = await getProducts()
  return <ProductGrid products={products} />
}
```

### ❌ WRONG — Component imports directly from `lib/data/`

```jsx
// app/(marketing)/products/page.jsx
import { products } from '@/lib/data/products'   // ❌ bypasses the API layer

export default async function ProductsPage() {
  return <ProductGrid products={products} />
}
```

If every component imports `lib/data/` directly, you'll have to hunt down and update
dozens of files when the backend is ready. If only `lib/api/` imports `lib/data/`,
you change one file and every component works instantly.

---

## How `lib/api/` Files Are Structured Now (Static Phase)

Each fetcher wraps static data in an async function — the same signature the real API will use.

```js
// src/lib/api/products.js
import 'server-only'

import { products } from '@/lib/data/products'   // ← only place lib/data is imported

export async function getProducts() {
  return products
}

export async function getProductBySlug(slug) {
  return products.find((p) => p.slug === slug) ?? null
}

export async function getProductsByCategory(category) {
  return products.filter((p) => p.category === category)
}
```

```js
// src/lib/api/services.js
import 'server-only'

import { services } from '@/lib/data/services'

export async function getServices() {
  return services
}

export async function getServiceBySlug(slug) {
  return services.find((s) => s.slug === slug) ?? null
}
```

---

## How `lib/api/` Files Will Look After Backend Is Ready

Only the function body changes. The function name, signature, and return shape stay identical — so every component and page that calls them requires zero changes.

```js
// src/lib/api/products.js  ← AFTER backend is ready
import 'server-only'

const API_BASE = process.env.API_BASE_URL

export async function getProducts() {
  const res = await fetch(`${API_BASE}/products`, { next: { revalidate: 3600 } })
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch products')
  return res.json()
}

export async function getProductBySlug(slug) {
  const res = await fetch(`${API_BASE}/products/${slug}`, { next: { revalidate: 3600 } })
  if (!res.ok) return null
  return res.json()
}
```

The page that calls `getProducts()` never needs to know the difference.

---

## Form Submissions — Always Go Through `/api/` Route Handlers

Even now, form submissions must POST to `app/api/` route handlers — never call a service function directly from a Client Component.

```jsx
// ✅ CORRECT — Client Component posts to route handler
// src/features/contact/ContactForm.jsx
"use client"

async function onSubmit(data) {
  const res = await fetch('/api/contact', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify(data),
  })
}
```

```js
// ✅ CORRECT — Route handler calls lib/api/ service
// app/api/contact/route.js
import { sendContactEmail } from '@/lib/api/contact'

export async function POST(req) {
  // validate → call lib/api/ → respond
}
```

```jsx
// ❌ WRONG — Client Component importing server logic directly
import { sendContactEmail } from '@/lib/api/contact'   // ❌ server-only will break build

async function onSubmit(data) {
  await sendContactEmail(data)   // ❌ never call server functions from client
}
```

When the backend is ready, only the `lib/api/contact.js` body changes (from nodemailer to an HTTP call). The form component and route handler stay the same.

---

## Required `lib/api/` Files for This Project

Each of these must exist and be the only access point for their domain:

| File | Functions to expose |
|---|---|
| `src/lib/api/products.js` | `getProducts()`, `getProductBySlug(slug)`, `getProductsByCategory(category)` |
| `src/lib/api/services.js` | `getServices()`, `getServiceBySlug(slug)` |
| `src/lib/api/industries.js` | `getIndustries()`, `getIndustryBySlug(slug)` |
| `src/lib/api/projects.js` | `getProjects()`, `getRecentProjects(limit)` |
| `src/lib/api/partners.js` | `getPartners()` |
| `src/lib/api/faqs.js` | `getFaqs()`, `getFaqsByCategory(category)` |
| `src/lib/api/navigation.js` | `getNavigation()` |
| `src/lib/api/contact.js` | `sendContactEmail(data)` |

Every file starts with `import 'server-only'` on line 1.

---

## Summary: The Two Rules

1. **Read data** → always through `src/lib/api/`, never from `src/lib/data/` directly in components
2. **Write data / submit forms** → always through `app/api/route.js` handlers, never by calling server functions from client components
